{"title_page": "Almond milk", "text_new": "{{short description|plant milk manufactured from almonds}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name = Almond milk\n| image = Home-made almond milk, November 2012.jpg\n| caption = \n| alternate_name = \n| serving_size = 100 g\n| calories = 15\n| protein = 0.59\n| fat = 1.10\n| carbohydrate = 0.58\n| glycemic_index = \n| other = \n}}\n'''Almond milk''' is a [[plant milk]] manufactured from [[almond]]s with a creamy texture and nutty flavor,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lincoln|first1=Jamie|title=Ditching Dairy? Here\u2019s a Cheat Sheet to the Tastiest Milk Alternatives|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/dairy-free-milk-alternatives-almond-coconut-cashew-rice-hemp|publisher=Vogue|accessdate=8 February 2018|date=18 August 2016}}</ref> although some types or brands are flavored in imitation of [[dairy milk]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/restaurants/face-off-almond-milk-vs-soy-milk-6402004|title=Face Off: Almond Milk vs. Soy Milk|work=Geri Maria Harris|publisher=Houston Press}}</ref> It does not contain [[cholesterol]], [[saturated fat]] or [[lactose]], and is often consumed by those who are [[Lactose intolerance|lactose-intolerant]] and others, such as [[veganism|vegans]] who avoid [[dairy product]]s. Commercial almond milk comes in sweetened, unsweetened, vanilla and chocolate flavors, and is usually [[food fortification|fortified]] with [[micronutrient]]s. It can also be made at home using a blender, almonds and water.<ref name=pros>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/the-pros-and-cons-of-almond-milk/story-fn6jaj16-1225984312290\n| title=The pros and cons of almond milk\n| last=Larmer\n| first=Christina\n| date=9 January 2011\n| publisher=[[Adelaide Now]]}}</ref>\n\nGlobal almond milk sales in 2018 were US$5.8 billion, growing at 14% per year, and forecast to be a $13 billion global market by 2025.<ref name=\"vn\">{{cite web |author1=Anna Starostinetskaya |title=Almond milk market to be worth $13.3 billion by 2025 |url=https://vegnews.com/2019/6/almond-milk-market-to-be-worth-133-billion-by-2025 |publisher=VegNews, Fresh Healthy Media |accessdate=27 September 2019 |date=23 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 220\n | header = Commercial almond milks\n | image1 =\n | alt1 = photograph\n | caption1 = Almond Breeze by [[Blue Diamond Growers]]\n | image2 =\n | caption2 = So Delicious by [[WhiteWave Foods]]\n | alt2 = photograph\n | image3 = \n | caption3 = [[Silk (plant milk)|Silk]] by [[WhiteWave Foods]]\n | alt3 = photograph\n}}\nAlmond milk was first invented in the Islamic Middle East and appears in cookbooks of the region from the 13th century onward, where it would later spread from the [[Levant]] to [[Europe]].<ref>{{citation |last=Al-Baghdadi |first=Muhammad bin Hasan |authormask=[[Muhammad bin Hasan al-Baghdadi]] |title=The Book of Dishes ''[\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0628\u064a\u062e, ''Kitab al-\u1e6cab\u012b\u1e2b'']'' |date=1226 |location=Baghdad}}. {{in lang|ar}}</ref> In the [[Middle Ages]], almond milk was known in both the [[Islamic world]] and [[Christendom]]. As a [[nut (fruit)|nut]], almonds are permitted for consumption by these religions during fasting seasons, such as [[Lent]] and [[Ramadan]]. Historian [[Carolyn Walker Bynum]] notes that \"medieval cookbooks suggest that the aristocracy observed fasting strictly, if legalistically. Meat-day and fish-day recipes were not separated in medieval recipe collections, as they were in later, better-organized cookbooks. But the most basic dishes were given in fast-day as well as\nordinary-day versions. For example, a thin split-pea puree, sometimes enriched with fish stock or almond milk (produced by simmering ground almonds in water), replaced meat broth on fast days; and almond milk was a general (and expensive) substitute for cow's milk.\"<ref name=\"Bynum\">{{Citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9DUgmJGxZyEC&pg=PA41&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjM5dyQr-vfAhWLDnwKHZwRBVkQuwUwAHoECAQQBA#v=onepage&f=false |title=Holy Feast and Holy Fast: The Religious Significance of Food to Medieval Women |publisher=University of California Press |author=Carolyn Walker Bynum |year=1988 |isbn= 978-0-520-06329-7 |page=41}}</ref>\nIn [[Persian cuisine]], an almond milk based dessert called ''harireh badam'' (almond gruel) is traditionally served during [[Ramadan]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ethnic and traditional Iranian rice-based foods|year=2016|volume=3|issue=2|pages=124\u2013134|author=Karizaki VM|journal=Journal of Ethnic Foods|url=http://www.journalofethnicfoods.net/article/S2352-6181(16)30037-3/fulltext}}</ref>\n\n==Commerce==\nIn the United States, almond milk remained a niche health food item until the early 2000s, when its popularity began to increase. In 2011 alone, almond milk sales increased by 79%.<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = https://finance.yahoo.com/news/almond-white-milk-dairy-alternatives-174100672.html\n |title        = With Almond as the New White Milk, Dairy Alternatives Make Further Inroads\n |work         = Marketwire\n |author       = David Sprinkle\n |date         = 19 January 2012\n |accessdate   = 14 October 2014\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20141023045038/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/almond-white-milk-dairy-alternatives-174100672.html\n |archive-date = 23 October 2014\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> In 2013, it surpassed [[soy milk]] as the most popular plant-based milk in the U.S.<ref name=\"soy milk fades\">{{cite web\n| url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-08-21/soy-milk-fades-as-americans-opt-for-drinkable-almonds\n| title=Soy Milk Fades as Americans Opt for Drinkable Almonds\n| first=Venessa\n| last=Wong\n| date=21 August 2013\n| publisher=[[BusinessWeek]]\n| accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref> As of 2014 it comprised 60 percent of plant-milk sales and 4.1 percent of total milk sales in the US.<ref>Senarath Dharmasena, Oral Capps, Jr., Brooke Kosub, [http://ageconsearch.umn.edu/bitstream/196789/2/Dharmasena_Capps_Kosub_Almond_milk_SAEA_2015%20%28paper%29.pdf \"Demand and Market Competitiveness of Almond Milk as a Dairy Alternative Beverage in the United States\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424071607/http://ageconsearch.umn.edu/bitstream/196789/2/Dharmasena_Capps_Kosub_Almond_milk_SAEA_2015%20%28paper%29.pdf |date=24 April 2016 }}, Department of Agricultural Economics and Agribusiness, Food and Consumer Economics Research Center, (AFCERC), Texas A&M University, 2015.</ref>{{rp|2\u20133}}\n\nCommon brands of almond milk include [[Blue Diamond Growers|Blue Diamond]]'s Almond Breeze and [[WhiteWave Foods]]' [[Silk (soy milk)|Silk]] PureAlmond.<ref name=\"soy milk fades\" />\n\nWithin the Italian regions of [[Sicily]], [[Apulia]], [[Calabria]], and [[Campania]], almond milk is a [[Prodotto agroalimentare tradizionale|protected traditional agricultural product]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.promobrindisi.com/download.asp?ln=&idtema=9&idtemacat=1&file=News/Files/298/guida.pdf|title=Guida ai Prodotti Tipici del Territorio di Brindisi|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Nutrition==\n{{Milk nutrition}}\nIf unfortified, almond milk has less vitamin&nbsp;D than fortified cows' milk; in North America cows' milk must be fortified with vitamin&nbsp;D, but vitamins are added to plant milks on a voluntary basis.<ref>Geoff Koehler, [http://www.stmichaelshospital.com/media/detail.php?source=hospital_news/2014/20141020_hn \"Children who drink non-cows\u2019 milk are twice as likely to have low vitamin&nbsp;D\"], St. Michael\u2019s Hospital, Toronto, 20 October 2014.</ref> Because of its low protein content, almond milk is not a suitable replacement for [[breast milk]], cows' milk, or hydrolyzed formulas for children under two years of age.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Keller MD, Shuker M, Heimall J, Cianferoni A |date= Jan 2012|title= Severe malnutrition resulting from use of rice milk in food elimination diets for atopic dermatitis|url=http://www.ima.org.il/FilesUpload/IMAJ/0/38/19354.pdf |journal=Isr Med Assoc J  |publisher= |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=40\u201342 |doi= |pmc= |pmid=22624441 }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe general production method involves soaking and grinding the almonds in an excess of water.  A milky white liquid is obtained after filtering the almond pulp (flesh). Almond milk can also be made by adding water to [[almond butter]]. In commercial production, the almond milk is homogenised with high pressure and pasteurised for greater stability and shelf life.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bernat |first1=N |last2=Chafer |first2=M |last3=Chiralt |first3=A |last4=Gonzalez-Martinez |first4=C |title=Development of a non-dairy probiotic fermented product based on almond milk and inulin |journal=Food Science and Technology International |date=2014 |doi=10.1177/1082013214543705}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, a [[class action lawsuit]] was placed in [[New York City|New York]] against two American manufacturers, [[Blue Diamond Growers]] and [[White Wave Foods]], for false advertising on the product label about the small amount of almonds (only 2%) actually in the final product.<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jesscollen/2015/07/23/is-2-almond-milk-more-confusing-than-2-cows-milk-blue-diamond-and-silk-probably-say-no/#3795da275943|title=Is 2% Almond Milk More Confusing Than 2% Cows Milk? Blue Diamond And Silk Probably Say 'No.'|publisher=Forbes|date=23 July 2015|author=Collen, Jess|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"lawsuit\">{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3967752/almond-milk-lawsuit/|publisher=Time Inc.|title=False Advertising Lawsuit Claims This Almond Milk Brand Doesn't Have Enough Almonds|author=Feeney, Nolan|date=29 July 2015|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Steven Trader |title=Almond Milk Buyers Fight Stay Pending Other False Ad Deal\n|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/805056/almond-milk-buyers-fight-stay-pending-other-false-ad-deal |date=8 June 2016 |newspaper=Law360}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Class action lawsuit targets Blue Diamond, Silk almond milks |url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/class-action-lawsuit-targets-blue-diamond-silk-almond-milks/article/2176230 |newspaper=Washington Examiner |date=8 June 2015}}</ref> In October 2015, a judge denied the consumers' request for an injunction.<ref>{{cite news|author=Joe Van Acker |title=Almond Milk Makers Duck Drinkers' Bid For Label Change |url=https://www.law360.com/articles/717204 |newspaper=Law360 |date=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Consumer demand===\nThe growth in consumer demand for almond milk in the early [[21st century]] accounted for one-quarter of the US almond supply, and its use in [[almond butter]] manufacturing tripled since 2011.<ref name=bloom/> Although there has been an increase of demand for alternative milks, usually due to things like [[veganism]], almond milk has been found to be detrimental to the environment due to the amount of water needed for cultivation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2019/jan/29/white-gold-the-unstoppable-rise-of-alternative-milks-oat-soy-rice-coconut-plant|title=White gold: the unstoppable rise of alternative milks|last=Franklin-Wallis|first=Oliver|date=2019-01-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-09-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2015/oct/21/almond-milk-quite-good-for-you-very-bad-for-the-planet|title=Almond milk: quite good for you \u2013 very bad for the planet|last=Saner|first=Emine|date=2015-10-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-09-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Sustainability ==\n{{Bar chart\n|title=Mean [[greenhouse gas emissions]] for one glass (200g) of different milks<ref name=Briggs/>|float=right|label_type=Milk Types|data_type=Greenhouse Gas Emissions (kg CO<small>2</small>-C<small>eq</small> per 200g)\n|bar_width=20\n|width_units=em\n|data_max=.62\n|label1=[[Milk|Cow's Milk]]\n|data1=0.62\n|label2=[[Rice Milk]]\n|data2=0.23\n|label3=[[Soy Milk]]\n|data3=0.21\n|label4=[[Oat Milk]]\n|data4=0.19\n|label5=[[Almond Milk]]\n|data5=0.16\n|color5=#CEF2E0\n}}\n{{Bar chart|title=Mean [[land use]] for one glass (200g) of different milks<ref name=\"Briggs\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-46654042|title=Which vegan milks are best for the planet?|last2=Briggs|first1=Clara |last1=Guibourg|first2=Helen|date=2019-02-22|access-date=2019-09-04|language=en-GB|work=BBC News: Science and Environment}}</ref>|float=right|label_type=Milk Types|data_type=Land Use (m<sup>2</sup> per 200g)\n|bar_width=20\n|width_units=em\n|data_max=1.81\n|label1=[[Milk|Cow's Milk]]\n|data1=1.81\n|label2=[[Oat Milk]]\n|data2=0.25\n|label3=[[Soy Milk]]\n|data3=0.23\n|label4=[[Almond Milk]]\n|data4=0.19\n|color4=#CEF2E0\n|label5=[[Rice Milk]]\n|data5=0.14\n}}\n\n\n{{Bar chart|title=Mean [[water footprint]] for one glass (200g) of different milks<ref name=Briggs/>\n|float=right\n|label_type=Milk Types\n|data_type=Water Use (L per 200g)\n|bar_width=20\n|width_units=em\n|data_max=131\n|label1=[[Milk|Cow's Milk]]\n|data1=131\n|label2=[[Almond Milk]]\n|color2= #CEF2E0\n|data2=74\n|label3=[[Rice Milk]]\n|data3=56\n|label4=[[Oat Milk]]\n|data4=9\n|label5=[[Soy Milk]]\n|data5=2\n\n}}\n\nAlmond production in California is concentrated mainly in the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]],<ref name=\"bi\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/amount-of-water-needed-to-grow-one-almond-orange-tomato-2015-4|title=Chart shows how some of your favorite foods could be making California's drought worse|date=8 April 2015|authors=Erin Brodwin, Samantha Lee |work=Business Insider|access-date=17 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>  where the mild climate, rich soil, abundant sunshine and water supply make for ideal growing conditions. Due to the [[Droughts in California|persistent droughts in California]] in the early [[21st century]], it became more difficult to raise almonds in a sustainable manner.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web |author1=Richard Gonzalez |title=How Almonds Became A Scapegoat For California's Drought |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2015/04/16/399958203/how-almonds-became-a-scapegoat-for-californias-drought |publisher=US National Public Radio |accessdate=16 April 2019 |date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bloom\">{{cite web |author1=Alan Bjerga |author2=Donna Cohen |author3=Cindy Hoffman |title=California Almonds Are Back After Four Years of Brutal Drought |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2018-thirst-for-almonds/ |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> \n\nAlmond sustainability is challenged because of the high amount of water needed to grow almonds: a single glass of almond milk requires roughly {{convert|74|litre}} of water to produce.<ref name=Briggs/> Among plant-based milks, almond milk requires substantially more water during the growing and production stages than soy, rice or oat milk (graph).<ref name=Briggs/> Cow's milk requires more water to produce than almond milk, and in 2014, California produced 42.3 billion pounds of cow's milk, while in the same year California produced only 2.14 billion pounds of almonds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.californiadairypressroom.com/Press_Kit/Dairy_Industry_Facts|title=Real California Milk Facts|last=|first=|date=|website=The California Dairy Press Room|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agmrc.org/commodities-products/nuts/almonds|title=Almonds {{!}} Agricultural Marketing Resource Center|website=www.agmrc.org|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n\nSustainability strategies implemented by the Almond Board of California and almond farmers include:<ref name=bloom/><ref name=\"abc2018\">{{cite web |title=Annual report: Growing Good - Almond Sustainability 2018 |url=https://newsroom.almonds.com/sites/default/files/pdf_file/Growing%20Good%202018.pdf |publisher=Almond Board of California |accessdate=16 April 2019 |date=2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Almond industry forerunner of future farm practices, sustainability program internationally recognized |url=https://www.farmprogress.com/tree-nuts/almond-industry-forerunner-future-farm-practices-sustainability-program-internationally |publisher=Western FarmPress |accessdate=16 April 2019 |date=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n* tree and soil health, and other farming practices\n* minimizing dust production during the harvest\n* [[bee]] health\n* [[irrigation]] guidelines for farmers\n* food safety\n* use of waste [[biomass]] as coproducts with a goal to achieve zero waste\n* use of [[solar energy]] during processing\n* job development\n* support of [[scientific research]] to investigate potential health benefits of consuming almonds\n* international education about sustainability practices\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food|Drink}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Cashew milk]]\n*[[Coconut milk]]\n*[[Hemp milk]]\n*[[Nut milk]]\n*[[Oat milk]]\n*[[Pea milk]]\n*[[Plant milk]]\n*[[Rice milk]]\n*[[Soy milk]]\n*[[Walnut milk]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Plant milk}}\n{{Milk by provenance}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almond Milk}}\n[[Category:Almonds]]\n[[Category:Animal product analogs]]\n[[Category:Cold drinks]]\n[[Category:Imitation foods]]\n[[Category:Medieval cuisine]]\n[[Category:Milk|Substitutes]]\n[[Category:Milk substitutes]]\n[[Category:Non-alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:Plant milk]]\n[[Category:Vegan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Vegetarianism and drinks]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|plant milk manufactured from almonds}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name = Almond milk\n| image = Home-made almond milk, November 2012.jpg\n| caption = \n| alternate_name = \n| serving_size = 100 g\n| calories = 15\n| protein = 0.59\n| fat = 1.10\n| carbohydrate = 0.58\n| glycemic_index = \n| other = \n}}\n'''Almond milk''' is a [[plant milk]] manufactured from [[almond]]s with a creamy texture and nutty flavor,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lincoln|first1=Jamie|title=Ditching Dairy? Here\u2019s a Cheat Sheet to the Tastiest Milk Alternatives|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/dairy-free-milk-alternatives-almond-coconut-cashew-rice-hemp|publisher=Vogue|accessdate=8 February 2018|date=18 August 2016}}</ref> although some types or brands are flavored in imitation of [[dairy milk]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/restaurants/face-off-almond-milk-vs-soy-milk-6402004|title=Face Off: Almond Milk vs. Soy Milk|work=Geri Maria Harris|publisher=HoustenPress}}</ref> It does not contain [[cholesterol]], [[saturated fat]] or [[lactose]], and is often consumed by those who are [[Lactose intolerance|lactose-intolerant]] and others, such as [[veganism|vegans]] who avoid [[dairy product]]s. Commercial almond milk comes in sweetened, unsweetened, vanilla and chocolate flavors, and is usually [[food fortification|fortified]] with [[micronutrient]]s. It can also be made at home using a blender, almonds and water.<ref name=pros>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/the-pros-and-cons-of-almond-milk/story-fn6jaj16-1225984312290\n| title=The pros and cons of almond milk\n| last=Larmer\n| first=Christina\n| date=9 January 2011\n| publisher=[[Adelaide Now]]}}</ref>\n\nGlobal almond milk sales in 2018 were US$5.8 billion, growing at 14% per year, and forecast to be a $13 billion global market by 2025.<ref name=\"vn\">{{cite web |author1=Anna Starostinetskaya |title=Almond milk market to be worth $13.3 billion by 2025 |url=https://vegnews.com/2019/6/almond-milk-market-to-be-worth-133-billion-by-2025 |publisher=VegNews, Fresh Healthy Media |accessdate=27 September 2019 |date=23 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 220\n | header = Commercial almond milks\n | image1 =\n | alt1 = photograph\n | caption1 = Almond Breeze by [[Blue Diamond Growers]]\n | image2 =\n | caption2 = So Delicious by [[WhiteWave Foods]]\n | alt2 = photograph\n | image3 = \n | caption3 = [[Silk (plant milk)|Silk]] by [[WhiteWave Foods]]\n | alt3 = photograph\n}}\nAlmond milk was first invented in the Islamic Middle East and appears in cookbooks of the region from the 13th century onward, where it would later spread from the [[Levant]] to [[Europe]].<ref>{{citation |last=Al-Baghdadi |first=Muhammad bin Hasan |authormask=[[Muhammad bin Hasan al-Baghdadi]] |title=The Book of Dishes ''[\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0628\u064a\u062e, ''Kitab al-\u1e6cab\u012b\u1e2b'']'' |date=1226 |location=Baghdad}}. {{in lang|ar}}</ref> In the [[Middle Ages]], almond milk was known in both the [[Islamic world]] and [[Christendom]]. As a [[nut (fruit)|nut]], almonds are permitted for consumption by these religions during fasting seasons, such as [[Lent]] and [[Ramadan]]. Historian [[Carolyn Walker Bynum]] notes that \"medieval cookbooks suggest that the aristocracy observed fasting strictly, if legalistically. Meat-day and fish-day recipes were not separated in medieval recipe collections, as they were in later, better-organized cookbooks. But the most basic dishes were given in fast-day as well as\nordinary-day versions. For example, a thin split-pea puree, sometimes enriched with fish stock or almond milk (produced by simmering ground almonds in water), replaced meat broth on fast days; and almond milk was a general (and expensive) substitute for cow's milk.\"<ref name=\"Bynum\">{{Citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9DUgmJGxZyEC&pg=PA41&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjM5dyQr-vfAhWLDnwKHZwRBVkQuwUwAHoECAQQBA#v=onepage&f=false |title=Holy Feast and Holy Fast: The Religious Significance of Food to Medieval Women |publisher=University of California Press |author=Carolyn Walker Bynum |year=1988 |isbn= 978-0-520-06329-7 |page=41}}</ref>\nIn [[Persian cuisine]], an almond milk based dessert called ''harireh badam'' (almond gruel) is traditionally served during [[Ramadan]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ethnic and traditional Iranian rice-based foods|year=2016|volume=3|issue=2|pages=124\u2013134|author=Karizaki VM|journal=Journal of Ethnic Foods|url=http://www.journalofethnicfoods.net/article/S2352-6181(16)30037-3/fulltext}}</ref>\n\n==Commerce==\nIn the United States, almond milk remained a niche health food item until the early 2000s, when its popularity began to increase. In 2011 alone, almond milk sales increased by 79%.<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = https://finance.yahoo.com/news/almond-white-milk-dairy-alternatives-174100672.html\n |title        = With Almond as the New White Milk, Dairy Alternatives Make Further Inroads\n |work         = Marketwire\n |author       = David Sprinkle\n |date         = 19 January 2012\n |accessdate   = 14 October 2014\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20141023045038/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/almond-white-milk-dairy-alternatives-174100672.html\n |archive-date = 23 October 2014\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> In 2013, it surpassed [[soy milk]] as the most popular plant-based milk in the U.S.<ref name=\"soy milk fades\">{{cite web\n| url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-08-21/soy-milk-fades-as-americans-opt-for-drinkable-almonds\n| title=Soy Milk Fades as Americans Opt for Drinkable Almonds\n| first=Venessa\n| last=Wong\n| date=21 August 2013\n| publisher=[[BusinessWeek]]\n| accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref> As of 2014 it comprised 60 percent of plant-milk sales and 4.1 percent of total milk sales in the US.<ref>Senarath Dharmasena, Oral Capps, Jr., Brooke Kosub, [http://ageconsearch.umn.edu/bitstream/196789/2/Dharmasena_Capps_Kosub_Almond_milk_SAEA_2015%20%28paper%29.pdf \"Demand and Market Competitiveness of Almond Milk as a Dairy Alternative Beverage in the United States\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424071607/http://ageconsearch.umn.edu/bitstream/196789/2/Dharmasena_Capps_Kosub_Almond_milk_SAEA_2015%20%28paper%29.pdf |date=24 April 2016 }}, Department of Agricultural Economics and Agribusiness, Food and Consumer Economics Research Center, (AFCERC), Texas A&M University, 2015.</ref>{{rp|2\u20133}}\n\nCommon brands of almond milk include [[Blue Diamond Growers|Blue Diamond]]'s Almond Breeze and [[WhiteWave Foods]]' [[Silk (soy milk)|Silk]] PureAlmond.<ref name=\"soy milk fades\" />\n\nWithin the Italian regions of [[Sicily]], [[Apulia]], [[Calabria]], and [[Campania]], almond milk is a [[Prodotto agroalimentare tradizionale|protected traditional agricultural product]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.promobrindisi.com/download.asp?ln=&idtema=9&idtemacat=1&file=News/Files/298/guida.pdf|title=Guida ai Prodotti Tipici del Territorio di Brindisi|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Nutrition==\n{{Milk nutrition}}\nIf unfortified, almond milk has less vitamin&nbsp;D than fortified cows' milk; in North America cows' milk must be fortified with vitamin&nbsp;D, but vitamins are added to plant milks on a voluntary basis.<ref>Geoff Koehler, [http://www.stmichaelshospital.com/media/detail.php?source=hospital_news/2014/20141020_hn \"Children who drink non-cows\u2019 milk are twice as likely to have low vitamin&nbsp;D\"], St. Michael\u2019s Hospital, Toronto, 20 October 2014.</ref> Because of its low protein content, almond milk is not a suitable replacement for [[breast milk]], cows' milk, or hydrolyzed formulas for children under two years of age.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Keller MD, Shuker M, Heimall J, Cianferoni A |date= Jan 2012|title= Severe malnutrition resulting from use of rice milk in food elimination diets for atopic dermatitis|url=http://www.ima.org.il/FilesUpload/IMAJ/0/38/19354.pdf |journal=Isr Med Assoc J  |publisher= |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=40\u201342 |doi= |pmc= |pmid=22624441 }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe general production method involves soaking and grinding the almonds in an excess of water.  A milky white liquid is obtained after filtering the almond pulp (flesh). Almond milk can also be made by adding water to [[almond butter]]. In commercial production, the almond milk is homogenised with high pressure and pasteurised for greater stability and shelf life.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bernat |first1=N |last2=Chafer |first2=M |last3=Chiralt |first3=A |last4=Gonzalez-Martinez |first4=C |title=Development of a non-dairy probiotic fermented product based on almond milk and inulin |journal=Food Science and Technology International |date=2014 |doi=10.1177/1082013214543705}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, a [[class action lawsuit]] was placed in [[New York City|New York]] against two American manufacturers, [[Blue Diamond Growers]] and [[White Wave Foods]], for false advertising on the product label about the small amount of almonds (only 2%) actually in the final product.<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jesscollen/2015/07/23/is-2-almond-milk-more-confusing-than-2-cows-milk-blue-diamond-and-silk-probably-say-no/#3795da275943|title=Is 2% Almond Milk More Confusing Than 2% Cows Milk? Blue Diamond And Silk Probably Say 'No.'|publisher=Forbes|date=23 July 2015|author=Collen, Jess|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"lawsuit\">{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3967752/almond-milk-lawsuit/|publisher=Time Inc.|title=False Advertising Lawsuit Claims This Almond Milk Brand Doesn't Have Enough Almonds|author=Feeney, Nolan|date=29 July 2015|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Steven Trader |title=Almond Milk Buyers Fight Stay Pending Other False Ad Deal\n|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/805056/almond-milk-buyers-fight-stay-pending-other-false-ad-deal |date=8 June 2016 |newspaper=Law360}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Class action lawsuit targets Blue Diamond, Silk almond milks |url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/class-action-lawsuit-targets-blue-diamond-silk-almond-milks/article/2176230 |newspaper=Washington Examiner |date=8 June 2015}}</ref> In October 2015, a judge denied the consumers' request for an injunction.<ref>{{cite news|author=Joe Van Acker |title=Almond Milk Makers Duck Drinkers' Bid For Label Change |url=https://www.law360.com/articles/717204 |newspaper=Law360 |date=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Consumer demand===\nThe growth in consumer demand for almond milk in the early [[21st century]] accounted for one-quarter of the US almond supply, and its use in [[almond butter]] manufacturing tripled since 2011.<ref name=bloom/> Although there has been an increase of demand for alternative milks, usually due to things like [[veganism]], almond milk has been found to be detrimental to the environment due to the amount of water needed for cultivation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2019/jan/29/white-gold-the-unstoppable-rise-of-alternative-milks-oat-soy-rice-coconut-plant|title=White gold: the unstoppable rise of alternative milks|last=Franklin-Wallis|first=Oliver|date=2019-01-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-09-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2015/oct/21/almond-milk-quite-good-for-you-very-bad-for-the-planet|title=Almond milk: quite good for you \u2013 very bad for the planet|last=Saner|first=Emine|date=2015-10-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-09-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Sustainability ==\n{{Bar chart\n|title=Mean [[greenhouse gas emissions]] for one glass (200g) of different milks<ref name=Briggs/>|float=right|label_type=Milk Types|data_type=Greenhouse Gas Emissions (kg CO<small>2</small>-C<small>eq</small> per 200g)\n|bar_width=20\n|width_units=em\n|data_max=.62\n|label1=[[Milk|Cow's Milk]]\n|data1=0.62\n|label2=[[Rice Milk]]\n|data2=0.23\n|label3=[[Soy Milk]]\n|data3=0.21\n|label4=[[Oat Milk]]\n|data4=0.19\n|label5=[[Almond Milk]]\n|data5=0.16\n|color5=#CEF2E0\n}}\n{{Bar chart|title=Mean [[land use]] for one glass (200g) of different milks<ref name=\"Briggs\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-46654042|title=Which vegan milks are best for the planet?|last2=Briggs|first1=Clara |last1=Guibourg|first2=Helen|date=2019-02-22|access-date=2019-09-04|language=en-GB|work=BBC News: Science and Environment}}</ref>|float=right|label_type=Milk Types|data_type=Land Use (m<sup>2</sup> per 200g)\n|bar_width=20\n|width_units=em\n|data_max=1.81\n|label1=[[Milk|Cow's Milk]]\n|data1=1.81\n|label2=[[Oat Milk]]\n|data2=0.25\n|label3=[[Soy Milk]]\n|data3=0.23\n|label4=[[Almond Milk]]\n|data4=0.19\n|color4=#CEF2E0\n|label5=[[Rice Milk]]\n|data5=0.14\n}}\n\n\n{{Bar chart|title=Mean [[water footprint]] for one glass (200g) of different milks<ref name=Briggs/>\n|float=right\n|label_type=Milk Types\n|data_type=Water Use (L per 200g)\n|bar_width=20\n|width_units=em\n|data_max=131\n|label1=[[Milk|Cow's Milk]]\n|data1=131\n|label2=[[Almond Milk]]\n|color2= #CEF2E0\n|data2=74\n|label3=[[Rice Milk]]\n|data3=56\n|label4=[[Oat Milk]]\n|data4=9\n|label5=[[Soy Milk]]\n|data5=2\n\n}}\n\nAlmond production in California is concentrated mainly in the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]],<ref name=\"bi\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/amount-of-water-needed-to-grow-one-almond-orange-tomato-2015-4|title=Chart shows how some of your favorite foods could be making California's drought worse|date=8 April 2015|authors=Erin Brodwin, Samantha Lee |work=Business Insider|access-date=17 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>  where the mild climate, rich soil, abundant sunshine and water supply make for ideal growing conditions. Due to the [[Droughts in California|persistent droughts in California]] in the early [[21st century]], it became more difficult to raise almonds in a sustainable manner.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web |author1=Richard Gonzalez |title=How Almonds Became A Scapegoat For California's Drought |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2015/04/16/399958203/how-almonds-became-a-scapegoat-for-californias-drought |publisher=US National Public Radio |accessdate=16 April 2019 |date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bloom\">{{cite web |author1=Alan Bjerga |author2=Donna Cohen |author3=Cindy Hoffman |title=California Almonds Are Back After Four Years of Brutal Drought |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2018-thirst-for-almonds/ |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> \n\nAlmond sustainability is challenged because of the high amount of water needed to grow almonds: a single glass of almond milk requires roughly {{convert|74|litre}} of water to produce.<ref name=Briggs/> Among plant-based milks, almond milk requires substantially more water during the growing and production stages than soy, rice or oat milk (graph).<ref name=Briggs/> Cow's milk requires more water to produce than almond milk, and in 2014, California produced 42.3 billion pounds of cow's milk, while in the same year California produced only 2.14 billion pounds of almonds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.californiadairypressroom.com/Press_Kit/Dairy_Industry_Facts|title=Real California Milk Facts|last=|first=|date=|website=The California Dairy Press Room|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agmrc.org/commodities-products/nuts/almonds|title=Almonds {{!}} Agricultural Marketing Resource Center|website=www.agmrc.org|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n\nSustainability strategies implemented by the Almond Board of California and almond farmers include:<ref name=bloom/><ref name=\"abc2018\">{{cite web |title=Annual report: Growing Good - Almond Sustainability 2018 |url=https://newsroom.almonds.com/sites/default/files/pdf_file/Growing%20Good%202018.pdf |publisher=Almond Board of California |accessdate=16 April 2019 |date=2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Almond industry forerunner of future farm practices, sustainability program internationally recognized |url=https://www.farmprogress.com/tree-nuts/almond-industry-forerunner-future-farm-practices-sustainability-program-internationally |publisher=Western FarmPress |accessdate=16 April 2019 |date=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n* tree and soil health, and other farming practices\n* minimizing dust production during the harvest\n* [[bee]] health\n* [[irrigation]] guidelines for farmers\n* food safety\n* use of waste [[biomass]] as coproducts with a goal to achieve zero waste\n* use of [[solar energy]] during processing\n* job development\n* support of [[scientific research]] to investigate potential health benefits of consuming almonds\n* international education about sustainability practices\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food|Drink}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Cashew milk]]\n*[[Coconut milk]]\n*[[Hemp milk]]\n*[[Nut milk]]\n*[[Oat milk]]\n*[[Pea milk]]\n*[[Plant milk]]\n*[[Rice milk]]\n*[[Soy milk]]\n*[[Walnut milk]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Plant milk}}\n{{Milk by provenance}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almond Milk}}\n[[Category:Almonds]]\n[[Category:Animal product analogs]]\n[[Category:Cold drinks]]\n[[Category:Imitation foods]]\n[[Category:Medieval cuisine]]\n[[Category:Milk|Substitutes]]\n[[Category:Milk substitutes]]\n[[Category:Non-alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:Plant milk]]\n[[Category:Vegan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Vegetarianism and drinks]]\n", "name_user": "Zefr", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almond_milk"}
{"title_page": "Crassula alata", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|name = \n|image =\n|status=\n|status_system=\n|genus = Crassula\n|species = alata\n|authority = ([[Viv.]]) [[Alwin Berger|Berger]] \n|}}\n\n'''''Crassula alata''''' is a herb in the family [[Crassulaceae]] found in southern [[Australia]].<ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Crassula alata''|id=3136}}</ref>\n\nThe succulent [[Annual plant|annual]] herb typically grows to a height of {{convert|5|cm|in|1}}. It produces white flowers in the spring time between August and October in the [[southern hemisphere]].<ref name=FloraBase/>\n\nThe species was first formally described as ''Crassula alata'' by the [[botanist]] [[Alwin Berger]] in 1930 as part of the Engler & Prantl work ''[[Die Naturlichen Pflanzenfamilien]]''. Synonyms for the species include; ''Crassula tillaea'' as described by L.V.Lester-Garland in 1803 in the work ''A flora of the island of Jersey'', ''Tillaea alata'' as described by Viviani in 1830 in the work ''Plantarum aegyptiarum'' and ''Crassula tripartita'' as described by [[N.A.Wakef.|N.A.Wakefield]] in 1957 in the work ''Flora of Victoria: new species and other additions'' published in ''The Victorian Naturalist''.<ref name=at/>\n \nIt is an alien species to Western Australia but has become naturalised in many areas. The plant is commonly found in lawns and in and around carparks in the [[South West (Western Australia)|South West]], [[Peel (Western Australia)|Peel]] and [[Wheatbelt (Western Australia)|Wheatbelt]] regions.<ref name=FloraBase/> It is also found in other states including coastal area in [[South Australia]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].<ref name=at>{{cite web|url=http://bie.ala.org.au/species/http://id.biodiversity.org.au/node/apni/2918404|title=Crassula alata (Viv.) A.Berger|accessdate=8 September 2017|work=Atlas of Living Australia|publisher=Global Biodiversity Information Facility}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2671835}}\n\n[[Category:Crassula|alata]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1930]]\n[[Category:Flora of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Flora of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Western Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|name = \n|image =\n|status=\n|status_system=\n|genus = Crassula\n|species = alata\n|authority = ([[Viv.]]) [[Alwin Berger|Berger]] \n|}}\n\n'''''Crassula alata''''' is a herb in the ''[[Crassulaceae]]'' family found in southern [[Australia]].<ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Crassula alata''|id=3136}}</ref>\n\nThe succulent [[Annual plant|annual]] herb typically grows to a height of {{convert|5|cm|in|1}}. It produces white flowers in the spring time between August and October in the [[southern hemisphere]].<ref name=FloraBase/>\n\nThe species was first formally described as ''Crassula alata'' by the [[botanist]] [[Alwin Berger]] in 1930 as part of the Engler & Prantl work ''[[Die Naturlichen Pflanzenfamilien]]''. Synonyms for the species include; ''Crassula tillaea'' as described by L.V.Lester-Garland in 1803 in the work ''A flora of the island of Jersey'', ''Tillaea alata'' as described by Viviani in 1830 in the work ''Plantarum aegyptiarum'' and ''Crassula tripartita'' as described by [[N.A.Wakef.|N.A.Wakefield]] in 1957 in the work ''Flora of Victoria: new species and other additions'' published in ''The Victorian Naturalist''.<ref name=at/>\n \nIt is an alien species to Western Australia but has become naturalised in many areas. The plant is commonly found in lawns and in and around carparks in the [[South West (Western Australia)|South West]], [[Peel (Western Australia)|Peel]] and [[Wheatbelt (Western Australia)|Wheatbelt]] regions.<ref name=FloraBase/> It is also found in other states including coastal area in [[South Australia]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].<ref name=at>{{cite web|url=http://bie.ala.org.au/species/http://id.biodiversity.org.au/node/apni/2918404|title=Crassula alata (Viv.) A.Berger|accessdate=8 September 2017|work=Atlas of Living Australia|publisher=Global Biodiversity Information Facility}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2671835}}\n\n[[Category:Crassula|alata]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1930]]\n[[Category:Flora of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Flora of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Western Australia]]\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crassula_alata"}
